{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_vrtx_014SVkSUxfaVyiWJ4fNnqmaZ","type":"tool_result","content":"1\t# Design: Multiarch Tuning Operator\n2\t\n3\t## The Gate-Inspect-Mutate-Release Pipeline\n4\t\n5\tEvery pod admitted to the cluster passes through a four-stage pipeline if the namespace is not excluded:\n6\t\n7\t```\n8\tPod Created\n9\t    |\n10\t    v\n11\t[Mutating Webhook]\n12\tscheduling_gate_mutating_webhook.go\n13\t  - Checks CPPC namespaceSelector\n14\t  - Checks hardcoded exclusions (kube-*, operator ns, DaemonSet, nodeName set)\n15\t  - Adds spec.schedulingGates[{name: \"multiarch.openshift.io/scheduling-gate\"}]\n16\t  - Pod is now GATED — scheduler will not place it\n17\t    |\n18\t    v\n19\t[Pod Reconciler]\n20\tpod_reconciler.go  (watches status.phase=Pending only)\n21\t  - Detects scheduling gate presence\n22\t  - Verifies namespace still matches CPPC namespaceSelector\n23\t  - Retrieves imagePullSecrets\n24\t  - Calls image inspector for each container image\n25\t    |\n26\t    v\n27\t[Image Inspector]\n28\tpkg/image/inspector.go + cache.go + facade.go\n29\t  - Fetches image manifest from registry (with auth)\n30\t  - Parses OCI / Docker v2.2 manifest lists for supported architectures\n31\t  - Returns sets.Set[string] of architecture names\n32\t  - Results are cached in inspectionCache (cleared on global pull secret rotation)\n33\t    |\n34\t    v\n35\t[Pod Model — Affinity & Gate Removal]\n36\tpod_model.go\n37\t  - Computes intersection of architectures across all containers\n38\t  - Sets spec.affinity.nodeAffinity.requiredDuringSchedulingIgnoredDuringExecution\n39\t    with kubernetes.io/arch In [amd64, arm64, ...] MatchExpression\n40\t  - Optionally sets preferredDuringSchedulingIgnoredDuringExecution\n41\t    via NodeAffinityScoring plugin\n42\t  - Removes the scheduling gate\n43\t  - Adds label multiarch.openshift.io/scheduling-gate=removed\n44\t  - Pod is now RELEASED — scheduler places it on a compatible node\n45\t```\n46\t\n47\tIf image inspection fails and `fallbackArchitecture` is configured on the CPPC, the controller falls back to that architecture instead of retrying indefinitely. If inspection fails without a fallback, the controller retries up to `MaxRetryCount = 5` times.\n48\t\n49\t### Pod Lifecycle ASCII Diagram\n50\t\n51\t```\n52\tcreated ──► gated ──► [inspection] ──► affinity set ──► gate removed ──► scheduled\n53\t                           |\n54\t                   (failure + fallback?)\n55\t                           |\n56\t                     fallback arch ──► affinity set ──► gate removed ──► scheduled\n57\t                           |\n58\t                   (failure, no fallback, retries exhausted)\n59\t                           |\n60\t                     pod stays gated, event published, metric incremented\n61\t```\n62\t\n63\t## Four Execution Modes\n64\t\n65\tThe operator binary is designed to run as multiple separate deployments, each in a distinct mode. Only one mode flag may be set at a time (enforced by `validateFlags()` in `cmd/main.go`).\n66\t\n67\t| Mode flag | Leader election ID | Purpose |\n68\t|---|---|---|\n69\t| `--enable-operator` | `operator-208d7abd.multiarch.openshift.io` | Reconciles ClusterPodPlacementConfig CR; deploys/tears down the controller and webhook Deployments, RBAC, ServiceMonitor |\n70\t| `--enable-ppc-controllers` | `ppc-controllers-208d7abd.multiarch.openshift.io` | Pod placement controller: inspects images, sets nodeAffinity, removes gate; also runs GlobalPullSecretSyncer |\n71\t| `--enable-ppc-webhook` | `208d7abd.multiarch.openshift.io` (base ID) | Mutating admission webhook on path `/add-pod-scheduling-gate`; uses 16-worker ants pool for async event publishing |\n72\t| `--enable-enoexec-event-controllers` | `enoexecevent-controllers-208d7abd.multiarch.openshift.io` | Handles ENoExecEvent CRs produced by the eBPF daemon running on nodes |\n73\t\n74\t**Why each mode has its own leader election ID:** The operator and the operand controllers compete for leader election independently. If they shared a single leader election ID, a failover of the operator component would also disrupt pod reconciliation, and vice versa. Separate IDs allow each set of controllers to elect its own leader, providing independent high-availability domains.\n75\t\n76\tThe webhook mode uses the base ID because webhooks are stateless and typically run with multiple replicas behind a Kubernetes Service — the leader election for the webhook is less critical than for the controllers, and the base ID avoids conflicts with the other modes while remaining unique within the cluster.\n77\t\n78\t## The Singleton ClusterPodPlacementConfig\n79\t\n80\t`ClusterPodPlacementConfig` is a cluster-scoped CRD that can only have one instance, named `\"cluster\"` (enforced at admission time by the validation webhook in `api/v1beta1/clusterpodplacementconfig_webhook.go`).\n81\t\n82\t### The Informer Singleton Pattern\n83\t\n84\tOperand modes (controller and webhook) must never call the Kubernetes API directly to read the CPPC. Instead, they use the **CPPC informer singleton**:\n85\t\n86\t```\n87\tpkg/informers/clusterpodplacementconfig/\n88\t  └── CPPCSyncer — implements manager.Runnable\n89\t      - Watches the CPPC object via a field-indexed informer\n90\t      - Maintains an in-memory copy of the current CPPC\n91\t      - Exposes Get() for synchronous access without API calls\n92\t```\n93\t\n94\tThis pattern exists for two reasons:\n95\t\n96\t1. **Performance**: Pod reconciliation runs at `NumCPU * 4` concurrency. If each reconcile loop made a live API call for the CPPC, the API server would be overwhelmed under load.\n97\t2. **Runtime configurability**: When `logVerbosity` changes on the CPPC, the informer detects the change and updates the log level without requiring a pod restart.\n98\t\n99\tControllers read CPPC configuration through the informer, never via `mgr.GetClient().Get(...)`.\n100\t\n101\t## System Namespace Exclusion\n102\t\n103\tThe `shouldIgnorePod` function in `pod_model.go` applies hardcoded exclusions that **cannot be overridden by CPPC configuration**:\n104\t\n105\t```go\n106\tfunc (pod *Pod) shouldIgnorePod(...) bool {\n107\t    return utils.Namespace() == pod.Namespace ||   // operator's own namespace\n108\t           strings.HasPrefix(pod.Namespace, \"kube-\") || // all kube-* namespaces\n109\t           pod.Spec.NodeName != \"\" ||              // already scheduled\n110\t           pod.HasControlPlaneNodeSelector() ||    // control plane pods\n111\t           pod.IsFromDaemonSet() ||                // DaemonSet pods\n112\t           pod.isNodeSelectorConfiguredForArchitecture() && (...)\n113\t}\n114\t```\n115\t\n116\t**Important:** `openshift-*` and `hypershift-*` namespaces are NOT in this hardcoded list. They are excluded only if the CPPC `namespaceSelector` is configured appropriately. The recommended selector uses:\n117\t\n118\t```yaml\n119\tnamespaceSelector:\n120\t  matchExpressions:\n121\t    - key: multiarch.openshift.io/exclude-pod-placement\n122\t      operator: DoesNotExist\n123\t```\n124\t\n125\tWith that selector, any namespace labeled `multiarch.openshift.io/exclude-pod-placement` is excluded. Without a properly configured `namespaceSelector`, the webhook will gate pods in `openshift-*` namespaces, which can block critical workloads if the pod-placement-controller is unavailable.\n126\t\n127\t## Image Inspection Cache\n128\t\n129\tThe image inspection cache (`pkg/image/facade.go`, `cache.go`) is a facade singleton initialized once per process:\n130\t\n131\t```go\n132\tvar imageInspectionCache image.ICache = image.FacadeSingleton()\n133\t```\n134\t\n135\tThe `Facade` wraps a `cacheProxy` that:\n136\t- Returns cached architecture sets for previously seen image references\n137\t- Bypasses the cache when `skipCache=true` is passed (used after a failed inspection to retry)\n138\t- Clears the entire cache when `StoreGlobalPullSecret` is called (because the new secret may unlock previously inaccessible images or change accessible registries)\n139\t\n140\t**Why the cache matters:** Image manifest inspection involves a network round-trip to the registry for every container image. With `MaxConcurrentReconciles = NumCPU * 4` and pods potentially sharing images, an uncached system would make O(pods × containers) registry calls. The cache reduces this to O(unique images) in steady state.\n141\t\n142\tThe `imageInspectionCache` variable is package-level and intentionally exported for test overriding (see `TESTING.md`).\n143\t"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"20736c39-72fb-45b9-a2e7-f6872d60b5b3","uuid":"a3890209-08dc-46a0-b41a-6ded8520a48b","timestamp":"2026-07-20T17:02:08.994Z","tool_use_result":{"type":"text","file":{"filePath":"/Users/kpais/kpais-workspace/a_b_evals/repos/multiarch-tuning-operator-treatment/agentic/DESIGN.md","content":"# Design: Multiarch Tuning Operator\n\n## The Gate-Inspect-Mutate-Release Pipeline\n\nEvery pod admitted to the cluster passes through a four-stage pipeline if the namespace is not excluded:\n\n```\nPod Created\n    |\n    v\n[Mutating Webhook]\nscheduling_gate_mutating_webhook.go\n  - Checks CPPC namespaceSelector\n  - Checks hardcoded exclusions (kube-*, operator ns, DaemonSet, nodeName set)\n  - Adds spec.schedulingGates[{name: \"multiarch.openshift.io/scheduling-gate\"}]\n  - Pod is now GATED — scheduler will not place it\n    |\n    v\n[Pod Reconciler]\npod_reconciler.go  (watches status.phase=Pending only)\n  - Detects scheduling gate presence\n  - Verifies namespace still matches CPPC namespaceSelector\n  - Retrieves imagePullSecrets\n  - Calls image inspector for each container image\n    |\n    v\n[Image Inspector]\npkg/image/inspector.go + cache.go + facade.go\n  - Fetches image manifest from registry (with auth)\n  - Parses OCI / Docker v2.2 manifest lists for supported architectures\n  - Returns sets.Set[string] of architecture names\n  - Results are cached in inspectionCache (cleared on global pull secret rotation)\n    |\n    v\n[Pod Model — Affinity & Gate Removal]\npod_model.go\n  - Computes intersection of architectures across all containers\n  - Sets spec.affinity.nodeAffinity.requiredDuringSchedulingIgnoredDuringExecution\n    with kubernetes.io/arch In [amd64, arm64, ...] MatchExpression\n  - Optionally sets preferredDuringSchedulingIgnoredDuringExecution\n    via NodeAffinityScoring plugin\n  - Removes the scheduling gate\n  - Adds label multiarch.openshift.io/scheduling-gate=removed\n  - Pod is now RELEASED — scheduler places it on a compatible node\n```\n\nIf image inspection fails and `fallbackArchitecture` is configured on the CPPC, the controller falls back to that architecture instead of retrying indefinitely. If inspection fails without a fallback, the controller retries up to `MaxRetryCount = 5` times.\n\n### Pod Lifecycle ASCII Diagram\n\n```\ncreated ──► gated ──► [inspection] ──► affinity set ──► gate removed ──► scheduled\n                           |\n                   (failure + fallback?)\n                           |\n                     fallback arch ──► affinity set ──► gate removed ──► scheduled\n                           |\n                   (failure, no fallback, retries exhausted)\n                           |\n                     pod stays gated, event published, metric incremented\n```\n\n## Four Execution Modes\n\nThe operator binary is designed to run as multiple separate deployments, each in a distinct mode. Only one mode flag may be set at a time (enforced by `validateFlags()` in `cmd/main.go`).\n\n| Mode flag | Leader election ID | Purpose |\n|---|---|---|\n| `--enable-operator` | `operator-208d7abd.multiarch.openshift.io` | Reconciles ClusterPodPlacementConfig CR; deploys/tears down the controller and webhook Deployments, RBAC, ServiceMonitor |\n| `--enable-ppc-controllers` | `ppc-controllers-208d7abd.multiarch.openshift.io` | Pod placement controller: inspects images, sets nodeAffinity, removes gate; also runs GlobalPullSecretSyncer |\n| `--enable-ppc-webhook` | `208d7abd.multiarch.openshift.io` (base ID) | Mutating admission webhook on path `/add-pod-scheduling-gate`; uses 16-worker ants pool for async event publishing |\n| `--enable-enoexec-event-controllers` | `enoexecevent-controllers-208d7abd.multiarch.openshift.io` | Handles ENoExecEvent CRs produced by the eBPF daemon running on nodes |\n\n**Why each mode has its own leader election ID:** The operator and the operand controllers compete for leader election independently. If they shared a single leader election ID, a failover of the operator component would also disrupt pod reconciliation, and vice versa. Separate IDs allow each set of controllers to elect its own leader, providing independent high-availability domains.\n\nThe webhook mode uses the base ID because webhooks are stateless and typically run with multiple replicas behind a Kubernetes Service — the leader election for the webhook is less critical than for the controllers, and the base ID avoids conflicts with the other modes while remaining unique within the cluster.\n\n## The Singleton ClusterPodPlacementConfig\n\n`ClusterPodPlacementConfig` is a cluster-scoped CRD that can only have one instance, named `\"cluster\"` (enforced at admission time by the validation webhook in `api/v1beta1/clusterpodplacementconfig_webhook.go`).\n\n### The Informer Singleton Pattern\n\nOperand modes (controller and webhook) must never call the Kubernetes API directly to read the CPPC. Instead, they use the **CPPC informer singleton**:\n\n```\npkg/informers/clusterpodplacementconfig/\n  └── CPPCSyncer — implements manager.Runnable\n      - Watches the CPPC object via a field-indexed informer\n      - Maintains an in-memory copy of the current CPPC\n      - Exposes Get() for synchronous access without API calls\n```\n\nThis pattern exists for two reasons:\n\n1. **Performance**: Pod reconciliation runs at `NumCPU * 4` concurrency. If each reconcile loop made a live API call for the CPPC, the API server would be overwhelmed under load.\n2. **Runtime configurability**: When `logVerbosity` changes on the CPPC, the informer detects the change and updates the log level without requiring a pod restart.\n\nControllers read CPPC configuration through the informer, never via `mgr.GetClient().Get(...)`.\n\n## System Namespace Exclusion\n\nThe `shouldIgnorePod` function in `pod_model.go` applies hardcoded exclusions that **cannot be overridden by CPPC configuration**:\n\n```go\nfunc (pod *Pod) shouldIgnorePod(...) bool {\n    return utils.Namespace() == pod.Namespace ||   // operator's own namespace\n           strings.HasPrefix(pod.Namespace, \"kube-\") || // all kube-* namespaces\n           pod.Spec.NodeName != \"\" ||              // already scheduled\n           pod.HasControlPlaneNodeSelector() ||    // control plane pods\n           pod.IsFromDaemonSet() ||                // DaemonSet pods\n           pod.isNodeSelectorConfiguredForArchitecture() && (...)\n}\n```\n\n**Important:** `openshift-*` and `hypershift-*` namespaces are NOT in this hardcoded list. They are excluded only if the CPPC `namespaceSelector` is configured appropriately. The recommended selector uses:\n\n```yaml\nnamespaceSelector:\n  matchExpressions:\n    - key: multiarch.openshift.io/exclude-pod-placement\n      operator: DoesNotExist\n```\n\nWith that selector, any namespace labeled `multiarch.openshift.io/exclude-pod-placement` is excluded. Without a properly configured `namespaceSelector`, the webhook will gate pods in `openshift-*` namespaces, which can block critical workloads if the pod-placement-controller is unavailable.\n\n## Image Inspection Cache\n\nThe image inspection cache (`pkg/image/facade.go`, `cache.go`) is a facade singleton initialized once per process:\n\n```go\nvar imageInspectionCache image.ICache = image.FacadeSingleton()\n```\n\nThe `Facade` wraps a `cacheProxy` that:\n- Returns cached architecture sets for previously seen image references\n- Bypasses the cache when `skipCache=true` is passed (used after a failed inspection to retry)\n- Clears the entire cache when `StoreGlobalPullSecret` is called (because the new secret may unlock previously inaccessible images or change accessible registries)\n\n**Why the cache matters:** Image manifest inspection involves a network round-trip to the registry for every container image. With `MaxConcurrentReconciles = NumCPU * 4` and pods potentially sharing images, an uncached system would make O(pods × containers) registry calls. The cache reduces this to O(unique images) in steady state.\n\nThe `imageInspectionCache` variable is package-level and intentionally exported for test overriding (see `TESTING.md`).\n","numLines":143,"startLine":1,"totalLines":143}}}
